03854nam a22005655i 9780822392927DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223929277 a10.1515/97808223929272doi  a(DE-B1597)554570  a(OCoLC)662616909  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.A78 7aPER0040302bisacsh1 aKing, Homay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLost in Translation :bOrientalism, Cinema, and the Enigmatic Signifier /cHomay King. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (216 p.) :b30 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. THE ENIGMATIC SIGNIFIER -- t2. THE SHANGHAI GESTURE -- t3. THE CHINATOWN SYNDROME -- t4. THE GREAT WALL -- t5. THE LOST GIRLS -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a nuanced exploration of how Western cinema has represented East Asia as a space of radical indecipherability, Homay King traces the long-standing association of the Orient with the enigmatic. The fantasy of an inscrutable East, she argues, is not merely a side note to film history, but rather a kernel of otherness that has shaped Hollywood cinema at its core. Through close readings of The Lady from Shanghai, Chinatown, Blade Runner, Lost in Translation, and other films, she develops a theory of the "Shanghai gesture," a trope whereby orientalist curios and décor become saturated with mystery. These objects and signs come to bear the burden of explanation for riddles that escape the Western protagonist or cannot be otherwise resolved by the plot. Turning to visual texts from outside Hollywood which actively grapple with the association of the East and the unintelligible-such as Michelangelo Antonioni's Chung Kuo: Cina, Wim Wenders's Notebook on Cities and Clothes, and Sophie Calle's Exquisite Pain-King suggests alternatives to the paranoid logic of the Shanghai gesture. She argues for the development of a process of cultural "de-translation" aimed at both untangling the psychic enigmas prompting the initial desire to separate the familiar from the foreign, and heightening attentiveness to the internal alterities underlying Western subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAsians in motion pictures. 0aEast and West in motion pictures. 0aMotion picturesxPlots, themes, etc. 0aOrientalism. 0aStereotypes (Social psychology) in mass media. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822392927zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822392927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822392927.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles